[{"id":"VR930923","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The image shown consists of two figures, Figure 1 and 2. Figure 1 is labeled Before Interaction and consists of an xy plane with an electron located at the origin. A photon labeled lambda sub 0 is moving from the left to right along the x axis to the left of the electron. Figure 2 is labeled After Interaction and consists of the same xy plane. The electron is moving up and to the right along a line in the first quadrant at an angle phi above the x axis and the photon labeled lambda sub f is moving along a line down and to the right in the fourth quadrant at an angle theta below the x axis. There is a note below that the figures are not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR930923.g04.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">In an experiment, a photon of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> moves in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive x\"><math alttext=\"positive x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-direction toward an electron that is initially at rest at the origin of the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x y\"><math alttext=\"x y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></math></span></span>-plane, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. The photon and electron interact. The resulting photon of wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span> and the electron move in the directions that are at angles <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span> below and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"phi\"><math alttext=\"phi\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ϕ</mi></math></span></span> above the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-axis, respectively, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. The experiment is conducted as described.</p>\n</div></div>\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:1\"><li class=\"list_paragraph\">\n<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> is the same in all trials.</li></ul>\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:1\"><li class=\"list_paragraph\">\n<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta\"><math alttext=\"theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"phi\"><math alttext=\"phi\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ϕ</mi></math></span></span> differ between trials.</li></ul>\n</div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:Ai part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ai\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a)</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. On Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">sketch</span> the expected relationship between <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub f\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"cosine of theta\"><math alttext=\"cosine of theta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></math></span></span> for the experiment. <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> is indicated.</p></li></ul><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 3 shows the first quadrant of the coordinate plane. The horizontal axis is labeled cosine theta. The value 0 is indicated at the origin, the value 0.5 is indicated at approximately the middle of the axis, and the value 1 is indicated toward the right of the axis. The vertical axis is labeled lambda sub f. The value 0 is indicated at the origin, and the value lambda sub 0 is indicated at approximately the middle of the axis.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR930923.g05.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR930923_rubric"},{"id":"VR930923","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Aii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Aii\"><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. In one trial, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta equals theta sub 1\"><math alttext=\"theta equals theta sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>θ</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, and the kinetic energy of the electron after the interaction is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K sub 1\"><math alttext=\"K sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>K</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>.</p></li></ul><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K sub 1\"><math alttext=\"K sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>K</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>. Express your answer in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub 0\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"theta sub 1\"><math alttext=\"theta sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>θ</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate. Begin your derivation by writing a fundamental physics principle or an equation from the reference information.</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR930923_rubric"},{"id":"VR930923","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> why the condition <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"phi is less than or equal to 90 degrees\"><math alttext=\"phi is less than or equal to 90 degrees\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>90</mn><mi>°</mi></math></span></span> must be true in the experiment.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR930923_rubric"}]